<tr><td align="left" valign="bottom" width="98%"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/toptab.gif" width="98" height="10" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td><td align="left" valign="bottom" width="22">&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td bgcolor="#3F403F" width="98%" class="cheader"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></td><td bgcolor="3F403F" valign="top" align="right" width="22"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/topcorner.gif" width="23" height="22" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" align="right"></td></tr>
<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> Dark Lord Huffs Favorite Old Skool Darkside Cards<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.82)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=15560'>Jason "bigdaddy" Huffman</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=15560&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 9, 2006</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> SO I know what youre asking yourself. Why in the blue hell is this guy writing about old dark side cards?  Well, mostly for my own amusement.  Pure nostalgia really.  However, some of the newer players MIGHT benefit from reading this in that some of these cards can be very effective in the right situations, even in an era that has decks loaded with virtual cards.  It also pains me to see the light side winning all theses games. evil is supposed to always win (because good is dumb) so I cant just stand aside and do nothing.  Furthermore, based on the quality of articles up here, I figure why not.  This is my first article be gentle &#61514; <br />
<br />
Anyway these are cards that can pack a serious punch, and generally dont require many tricks to pull off.meaning. they dont require a lot of force, lots of cards in combination, destiny draws to work, and super-specific situations.  Often they lack a lot of counters so they will work uncontested also.  Also Im not saying these are the best old cards, Im just saying I think theyre cards that could still be used in many decks and they could see more play than they seem to now.  <br />
<br />
So, here we go.  <br />
<br />
I guess Ill start with premiere-hoth, which I consider the truly old-skool, and maybe add on more later.  <br />
<br />
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br />
Lets get things started out right with 2 classics.  Disarmed and Dr. Evazan.   Now I know you kids, with your newfangled Xbox 360s, Emo Rock, and all that nonsense, probably think the Dr E & Ponda B combo is where its at.  Well think again.  <br />
<br />
DISARMED<br />
If both players have a character with a weapon at same site, deploy on that opponent&#39;s character during any control phase (even opponent&#39;s control phase). Character loses weapon, is power -1 and may no longer carry weapons. (Immune to Alter.)<br />
<br />
DR. EVAZAN<br />
Adds 2 to power of anything he pilots. The not-so-good doctor may &#39;operate&#39; on any other character present that was just &#39;hit&#39; or just Disarmed; &#39;patient&#39; is lost.<br />
<br />
Note that his deploy is considerably cheaper, and he maintains the high destiny of Dr E& Ponda B.  Also you have to figure that the Dr E&PB combo will normally find itself at the same site as a lightsaber so you lose some power there also.  As far as I know you can also operate while piloting a combat vehicle. <br />
<br />
Bottom line this is a cheap and nearly foolproof way to auto-kill many jedi.  Everyone seems concerned about a lot of these tank jedi roaming around, this can be an easy solution.  Granted obi-wans journal can be a problem. But depending on the timing of the disarmed and fact that the journal is only at one site, disarmed can still be effective.<br />
<br />
Next up we have DATHCHA THE JAWA.  Ok just kidding.  I love you Dathcha.  <br />
<br />
----------------------------------------------------------<br />
IVE LOST ARTOO!<br />
Use 1 Force to target a starship&#39;s [nav computer] or astromech. Draw destiny. If destiny > 1, [nav computer] or astromech is lost. If starship&#39;s [nav computer] icon is lost, place Effect on starship (may add 1 astromech); otherwise, Effect lost.<br />
  <br />
Ok so I lied a bit when I started this article this card does of course require a destiny draw to work.  However, 2 or higher is a pretty reasonable draw in most decks.  My favorite use for this card is to use it in a space-focused deckstrand some light side ship at a system and then wait until I have enough stuff deployed elsewhere to consolidate at that system and commence beat-down.  Might also be useful if some really tough light side ship is chasing you and you want to effectively shake him.<br />
<br />
This goes well with my next favorite Old Skool card.  <br />
--------------------------------------------------------<br />
LATERAL DAMAGE  <br />
Deploy on any system. Target an opponent&#39;s starship. Target&#39;s power and forfeit = 0. When target reaches Utinni Effect, target draws one destiny. Utinni Effect canceled if destiny > 2. Otherwise, draw again next move phase, etc.<br />
<br />
This one deserves some special attention.  First off, like I said, you can combine it with Ive Lost Artoo (or gravity shadow for that matter) to isolate the opponents ships and cause overflow damage.  Generally speaking, it completely trashes an enemys ship. This card works in effect almost like a You are Beaten on the ground, in that even if the opponent has 2 ships at a location, its more like they only have 1 ship there for battling purposes.  Assuming they only have 1 ship there, even better.  Current light side small capitals like Bright Hope and Tantive IV are in my mind particularly susceptible given their low hyperspeed (hurts their ability to reach the utinni effect) and tendency of players to load up pilots on these ships to boost their power (the pilots add nothing other than their own forfeit when their ship has lateral damage on it).  <br />
<br />
Overall this is just a great game-winning card that should see more play than it does.  Its automatic, potentially devastating, and can find good use in any game with space interaction.  I caveat you do need at least 2 systems on the table.  <br />
-----------------------------------------------------------<br />
<br />
IMPERIAL CODE CYLINDER<br />
<br />
Ok this one is highly suspect but Im throwing it out there anyway. Lets look at the language that might have a use:<br />
<br />
If any Imperial leader is present with a Scomp link, you may: Glance at the cards in any Reserve Deck for 20 seconds. Shuffle, cut and replace.<br />
<br />
First off. Play this in the first turn or two to figure out the majority of the opponents deck.  While this doesnt show you whats in their hand, it might give you a good idea of whether (for example) they have no starships in their deck, allowing you to take control of systems quickly and with minimal stuff at the systems.  <br />
<br />
Also, this works like a bith shuffle if theyre tracking destiny draws.  <br />
<br />
OK so thats pretty blah. How about we move on to something better.<br />
-----------------------------------------------------------<br />
THE CIRCLE IS NOW COMPLETE<br />
If Vader and Obi-Wan are present at same site, use 1 Force to initiate a duel between them. Either Jedi is power +2 if they have a lightsaber. Loser of duel is placed out of play.<br />
<br />
I want to focus here on this non-epic duel usage of the card.  Im actually a Noob when it comes to this card because I never saw it used much over the years playing anyway, this is an awesome card especially taking into account how strong the new virtual Obi-Wan is, but its cool against the old Obi-Wans too.  Basically Lord Vader, given a lightsaber, automatically kills Obi and places him out of play no destiny is drawn so Virual Obis destiny-canceling text is irrelevant.  Seems like this card + you are beaten = 3rd light side character at the site gets beat down.  <br />
<br />
Another couple nice things about this card its a 6 destiny, and you can search for it with Bad Feeling Have I (v).  <br />
----------------------------------------------------------<br />
MOSEP     (A New Hope power 1, ability 1, deploy 3, forfeit 5, destiny 3)<br />
When opponent is losing Force from Force drains at the same or an adjacent site, lost Force must come from Reserve Deck if possible.<br />
<br />
If youre planning on doing a lot of damage via force drains on ground, this card could be of use.  Mosep can cause the opponent to lose key cards from their reserve and potentially disrupt their strategy, or at the very least, cause them to lose cards other than what theyd prefer to lsoe.  Employment in a Maul deck, scum turtling, walkers, or dark deal all seem reasonable.  He doesnt have to be present at the site to work you can throw him on a vehicle in your walker deck for example.  The 3 destiny doesnt hurt either.  <br />
-------------------------------------------------------<br />
TIE ASSAULT SQUADRON  Power 3, Ability 3, Destiny 3, Manuever 3, Forefit 6, Deploys in different ways.  <br />
<br />
Well Ive been sucking when using these lately, but I maintain theyre absolutely fantastic.  Why????  <br />
1) You retrieve 3 via seinar fleet systems every time you deploy them (as opposed to replacing them) (albeit you must save force to pay for it with aim high) (also if you deploy them with atmospheric assault youre losing that card and it could get grabbed)<br />
2) They cant be targeted by X-wing cannons (or anything specifically targeting starfighters or capital ships) because theyre not starfighters (squadrons can only be targeted as starships)  <br />
3) Their stats are ok, but are great with all power to weapons because it is treated as 3 TIES, so you get +6 power and immunity to attrition.<br />
4) Likewise, with a dreadnought, they gain +3 power.  <br />
5) Dreaded Imperial Starfleet (v) makes these completely broken Star Destroyers are pretty cheap to deploy these days, and every time you deploy one you can get one of these squadrons (for free) and deploy it from your reserve.  Note that you can do this multiple times in your deploy phase. So, say we deploy 2 star destroyers, we have about 16 power.  The 2 tie squadrons are 6 power total, but with all power to weapons it becomes 18 power for 34 total.  Again you only needed the all power to weapons and a couple destroyers in your hand to pull this off.  Throw a dreadnought in there for a few more force and youre up to 45 power in a hurry.  <br />
6) A not too terrible 3 destiny, and 6 forfeit if things turn south.  <br />
-------------------------------------------------------<br />
U-3PO (deploys for 3, destiny 3) <br />
Deploy on opponent&#39;s side as an Undercover spy (except that if present during a battle at a site, adds its power to Light Side). If spy&#39;s &#39;cover is broken,&#39; the above game text is canceled and Light Side may use as if stolen.<br />
<br />
Gotta love U-3PO.  I like Arica, but this guy is the best undercover spy option for the dark side.  Why?  Because if his cover is broken, hes not a liability.  Plus his destiny is higher and he deploys for less.  Sure his defense value isnt as high, but you gotta figure that the light side is going to hit Arica with their lightsaber anyway dont you?  By the way, why am I referring to U-3PO as he?  Hmmmmmmmmm.  Anyway I know undercover spies are far from fool-proof but this is only one card and it can still have a huge impact on the game.  <br />
---------------------------------------------------------<br />
EXPOSURE<br />
Use X force during your control phase, where X= the total number of characters (whether present or missing) at exterior marker sites under nighttime conditions.  Those characters are lost.<br />
<br />
Talk about a card that should piss the light side player off royally.  Id put it right up there with getting hit with a Oota-Goota after you play a nabrun.  Anyway I love this card. Oh so those pesky jedi are on hoth trying to whoop on your cute little imperial walkers?  Use a couple force and wave bye-bye.  So simple, yet so effective.  It doesnt prevent hit and runs, but anyone sticking around is a goner with this card.  I guess one downside is you dont want to have your own characters present at the sites, but hey its a walker deck so stick with the walkers already.  <br />
<br />
Anyway if you made it this far thanks for reading- hope you enjoyed it and maybe even picked up something new.  Let me know if you have other favorites that are along these lines.  <br />
<br />
